x4freetext: The target was a high-pressure gas cylinder of 25.7 cm
length and 2 cm radius with carbon-fiber/epoxy walls of
only 0.5 mm thickness to keep background and particle
For the three target nuclei studied, N, Ar, and Xe, the
target gas pressure was 40 bar, 28 bar, and 13 bar,
respectively.  The target temperature and pressure were
monitored during the experiment and stayed constant
within less than 1% throughout each specific
The detector consisted of a plastic scintillator
cylinder divided into 28 deltaE-E-E sectors, each 1.6 m
in active length.  The ends of the cylinder were closed
by endcaps, each consisting of 14 deltaE-E plastic
normally incident protons of up to 250 MeV.
The trajectory information for charged particles
was provided by two coaxial cylindrical multiwire
proportional chambers inside the plastic cylinder.
Their angular resolution was about 1 degree FWHM.
With the solid angle coverage of more than 98% of 4pi
and the low proton threshold of about 20 MeV, a large
fraction of the phase space was accessible to LADS
even at low incident pion energies.
The pi+ beam was defined by a set of plastic
scintillation detectors that counted the individual
pions and rejected particles in the beam halo.

The final normalisation errors were in the range 6%-10%
except at the lowest pion energy where it was 20%.
This error depends on the pion beam
